      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R1) with documented V&V pedigree and FDA-recognized software quality plan. Version control and audit trail maintained throughout simulation campaign.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023R1 is a commercially validated solver with an established software quality assurance program compliant with FDA guidance on software in medical devices. All simulation scripts and case files are version-controlled in a GIT repository with signed commits. A software quality plan was reviewed and approved prior to simulation execution, satisfying MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark test cases from FDA-recognized verification suite pass within solver tolerance. At least one analytical solution comparison documented.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver was verified against the FDA hemolysis benchmark suite including lid-driven cavity and backward-facing step cases. Numerical errors relative to analytical solutions were below 0.5% for velocity magnitude and below 1.2% for wall shear stress, confirming adequate code verification at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) less than 5% for primary QoI (hemolysis index) using at least three systematically refined mesh levels.",
      "rationale": "A formal Richardson extrapolation study was conducted using three mesh levels (2.1M, 5.8M, and 14.2M cells). GCI values for the hemolysis index ranged from 1.3% to 1.9% across the five operating points, well below the 5% acceptance threshold. The achieved level of 3 reflects the rigorous three-level refinement with formal uncertainty quantification, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented with traceability to clinical CPB operating envelope. Flow rates and rotational speeds within ±5% of simulation boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "The experimental hemolysis data used for validation was collected under controlled laboratory conditions replicating the clinical CPB operating envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Measured flow rates and pump speeds were within ±3.2% of the CFD boundary conditions. Blood analog fluid properties were characterized at 37°C and matched simulation inputs within measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index within 20% of experimental measurements for at least 4 of 5 operating points. Systematic bias documented if present.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. Prediction errors ranged from 4.1% to 17.8%, with all five points within the 20% acceptance band. A slight systematic over-prediction of 8.3% was observed and is attributed to the power-law hemolysis model constants calibrated on a different device geometry, which is documented as a model form uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to clinical decision criterion. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress, exposure time) support mechanistic interpretation.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index (RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate) is the direct regulatory acceptance criterion for Class II CPB devices and is computed as the primary QoI. Secondary QoIs including volume-averaged shear stress and scalar blood damage index provide mechanistic insight into hemolysis drivers. All QoIs are directly traceable to the clinical decision question regarding worst-case operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same device geometry or a sufficiently similar predicate. Operating conditions span the clinical envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the same geometry used in the regulatory submission. The five validation operating points span the full clinical flow-speed envelope from low-flow/low-speed to high-flow/high-speed conditions, ensuring the validation domain encompasses the COU decision space. The hemolysis measurement protocol followed ASTM F1841 with NIH normalization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; iterative convergence to residual tolerance of 1e-5 documented as sufficient.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, explicit numerical solver error quantification beyond iterative convergence monitoring is not required. Residuals for continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations were converged to 1e-6 for all operating points, and mass imbalance was below 0.01%. No further solver error assessment is warranted at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; standard operating procedures and peer review of simulation setup are sufficient controls.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at MRL 2. Simulation setup was peer-reviewed by a second qualified analyst prior to execution. Standard operating procedures for CFD setup, boundary condition assignment, and post-processing were followed and documented in the simulation report. Independent verification of mesh quality metrics was performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; use of established power-law hemolysis model with literature-sourced constants is acceptable.",
      "rationale": "Formal model form uncertainty quantification is not required at MRL 2. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is the established industry standard for CFD hemolysis prediction in rotary blood pumps and has been applied in multiple FDA-cleared device submissions. Model form limitations are acknowledged in the simulation report and the systematic over-prediction bias is documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; nominal input values with documented sources are sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Formal model input uncertainty propagation is not required at MRL 2. All boundary condition values (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, rotational speed, fluid properties) are specified at nominal values with documented sources traceable to the experimental test protocol and clinical device specifications. Sensitivity to ±10% variation in key inputs was qualitatively assessed and found not to alter the worst-case operating point identification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; single representative device unit used for validation experiments is acceptable.",
      "rationale": "Statistical characterization of device-to-device variability through multiple test samples is not required at MRL 2. Validation experiments were conducted on a single representative unit of the FDA generic centrifugal pump fabricated to nominal dimensions. Manufacturing tolerances for this device are well-characterized from prior FDA submissions and are not expected to materially affect hemolysis at the operating conditions studied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; documented mapping between experimental and simulation input parameters is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Formal equivalency analysis of input parameters between the validation experiment and the COU simulation is not required at MRL 2. A documented parameter mapping table confirms that all primary boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity, density) are matched between the experimental and simulation domains within measurement uncertainty. Differences in secondary parameters (inlet turbulence intensity, wall roughness) are noted and bounded by sensitivity analysis."
    }
